1 by a natural person who is the provider or is authorized to act for the provider,
2 under the pains and penalties of perjury.
3 2. In addition to the requirements of subsection 1, each application
4 submitted to participate as a provider must be [notarized.] accompanied by
5 verification of the identity and signature of the natural person who signed the
6 statement pursuant to subsection 1:
7 (a) By oath or affirmation of the person administered by a notary public or
8 other person authorized by law to administer oaths or affirmations; or
9 (b) Through an electronic identity verification system that is used or
10 approved by the Department for the purpose of verifying the identification or
11 signature of a person.
12 3. A person is guilty of perjury which is a category D felony and shall be
13 punished as provided in NRS 193.130 if the person signs or submits, or causes to be
14 signed or submitted, [such] a statement described in subsection 1 , knowing that
15 the application, report or invoice contains information which is false, in whole or in
16 part, by commission or by omission.
17 [3.] 4. For the purposes of this section, a person who signs on behalf of a
18 provider is presumed to have the authorization of the provider and to be acting at
19 the direction of the provider.
20 5. As used in this section, “electronic identity verification system” means an
21 electronic system that is capable of verifying the identity or signature of a person
22 by:
23 (a) Using multifactor authentication;
24 (b) Verifying data contained within governmental databases or appearing on
25 government-issued identification cards, including, without limitation,
26 photographs and signatures;
27 (c) Utilizing biometric data or facial recognition technology;
28 (d) Utilizing a combination of any mechanism described in paragraphs (a),
29 (b) and (c); or
30 (e) Utilizing other secure and accurate means or procedures.
31 Sec. 2. This act becomes effective on July 1, 2025.

